Author: mishkov
Content:
I think the part of FTL that i like most is how it's relatively simple but has just enough writing and whatnot to make your crew feel like they're developing a story, and then letting your brain fill in the gaps. There's something I find really cozy about a crew going on a scifi expedition, essentially making the craft an organism on that new scale.

I think a lot of other games try to emulate that but fail due to being over engineered.

... see i think complaining about moderation is more disruptive behaviour than actually spoiling the game. You're not a whistleblower exposing a dictatorial regime, you're a random chatter getting angry about being deprived of a privilege that's not owed to you in any way whatsoever. You're whining and you're calling for people to challenge an authority which is *actually way more invested in Joe's experience being high quality than you are.* Regardless of the extra timeouts, they are maintaining chat quality. Now don't get me wrong, there is a time for you to voice your opinions on moderation. When new mods are being added, or when Joe is interacting with chat or literally asking for your opinion. Author: aerolfos
Content: inscryption act 2 honestly felt very unfinished to me - and not because in universe its supposed to be, I mean the concept of an unfinished card game somehow felt unfinished

Author: aerolfos
Content: all 4 factions are properly implemented, they have deck variety, the mechanics all work, they have the full set of bosses and no big missing areas or stuff youd expect like that

Author: aerolfos
Content: but theyre woefully underexplained, woefully imbalanced, the areas take too long to get through for the content thats there, your progression is weird (some decks you should just dump for new cards you get) and skips from ‘weak’ to ‘won the game just need to actually do the fights’ with no real in between

Author: aerolfos
Content:
also if you get used to energy you have a leg up on act 3

the other stuff is useless, the colour symbols come back but they work differently and interplay in your deck in a different (actually useful) way so if you play with them in act 2 your experience is actively worse

Content: When taking a rare card watch out for ijaraq, you can tell if a card is ijaraq when getting cards if it has red eyes and has a question mark at the end of its name. If you take ijaraq then ijaraq will disguise itself as a random card in your deck (which I think changes every battle). It is impossible to discern ijaraq from the card it is copying until you try to play it. When you play ijaraq it transforms into a 4 1 card with the blocking sigil, buffs from the card it is replacing may carry over (I think sometimes I'm not 100% certain on how it works)

Author: _cliffracer
Content: yeah I think we're using different definitions of synergy here. I mean more that every deck wants to have robot, beast, and bone cards because otherwise you're leaving resources on the table. It's basically the opposite of how the mana systems work in MTG/Pokemon/wizard decks
